<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF206-961-608  </DOCNO><DOCID>06 961 608.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Jan 16 1989 v23 n2 p94(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Ups and downs of job hopping: employers weigh implications ofresumes indicating frequent changes. (Computer Careers) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ruhl, Janet.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Changing jobs every year or two has long been a simple solution tothe question of how to raise both salary and skill level forprogrammers.andP;  Job hopping can be an ongoing problem for MISmanagers, however.andP;  Managers sometimes eliminate candidates with arecord of frequent changes.andP;  One manager observes that a patternof jobs lasting three to six months is most disturbing.andP;  Onerecruiting consultant says most employees prefer employees whowork three or more years at a company, but the career patternprevalent among current employees is the major determining factorin attitudes towards job hoppers.andP;  Longevity in a previous job isnot a guarantee of an employee's performance.andP;  The employee's roleis a major factor in hiring, which can mitigate bias against jobhoppers.andP;  Job hopping is beneficial in the consulting field.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer industryManagement of EDPSalaryPersonnel Management.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>